02. Neural Network Classification with TensorFloe

We've seen how to work a regression problem in TensorFlow, now let's see it's approach in a classification problem.

A classification problem involves predicting whether a thing is one or the other. For example:

  • Predict whether someone has a heart disease or not, based on their health parameters. Binary Classification
  • Decide whether a photo is a food, person or dog, with multiple options to pick. Multi-class Classification
  • Predice what categories chould be assigned to a Wiki article. Where a single article has multiple possible categories to choose. Multi-label Classification

We'll be working through a variation of different classification problems.

What we're going to cover

  • Architevture of a classification model
  • Input shapes and output shapes
    • X: features/data (inputs)
    • y: label (outputs)
      • "What class do the inputs belong to?"
    • Creating custom data to view and fit
    • Steps in modelling for binary and multiclass classification
      • Creating a model
      • Compiling a model
        • Defining a loss function
        • Setting up an optimizer
          • Finding the best learning rate
        • Creating evaluation metrics
      • Fitting a model (getting it to find patterns in our data)
      • Improving a model
    • The power of non-linearity
    • Evaluating classification models
      • Visualizing the model ('visualize, visualize, visualize)
      • Looking at training curves
      • Compare predictions to ground truth (using our evluation metrics)

Typical architecture of a classification neural network

Typical is used purposely in this occaison.

Cuz architecture of classification neural network widely vary depending on the problem you're working on.

Though there are fundamentals all deep neural networks contain:

  • An input layer
  • Some hidden layers
  • An output layer

Much of the rest is up to the data analyst creating the model.

The following are some standard values you'll often use in your classification neural networks.

Hyperparameter Binary Classification Multiclass Classification
Input layer shape Based on number of features Same to binary classification
Hidden layer(s) Problem specific, min=1, max=inf Same to binary classification
Neurons per hidden layer Problem specific, generally 10 to 100 Same to binary classification
Output layer shape 1 (one class or the other) 1 per classification variable
Hidden activation Usually ReLU (rectified linear unit) Same as binary classification
Output activation Sigmoid Softmax
Optimizer SGD (stochastic gradient descent), Adam Same to binary classification

Table above was adapted from a thick ass uni text book ^

Creating data to view and fit

We can start by importing pre-existing classification dataset, but let's practice making our own classification data.

Note: It's common practice to have yourself build, model, and test on a simple dataset, before moving to the big boys. You rehearse yourself on this so called toy set before performing on the actual experiment.

As classification is predicting something as one thing or not, let's make a dataset to reflect that.

To do so, we'll use Scikit-Learn's make_circles() function.

In[5]:
from sklearn.datasets import make_circles

# Make 1000 examples
n_samples = 1000

# Create circles
X, y = make_circles(n_samples,
                    noise=0.03,
                    random_state=42)

Now we've formed data, let's check out X and y!

Input and output shapes

One of the most common issues you'll run into when building neural networks is shape mismatches. Aka the input and output shapes are not as what was expected, similar to what we've talked about in workbook 01.

Here, we want to input X and output y.

So let's check both their shapes.

In[11]:
# Check shapes of X and y
X.shape, y.shape
Out[11]:
((1000, 2), (1000,))
In[12]:
# Check length
len(X), len(y)
Out[12]:
(1000, 1000)

We got the same amount of X and y, which should always be the case. If not, then we need to do a bit of investigating and clean some data.

Let's check first example

In[13]:
# Check first example
X[0], y[1]
Out[13]:
(array([0.75424625, 0.23148074]), np.int64(1))

So now we've got two X Features, which leads to one y value.

For our neural network, this means accepting a one dimensional array that has 2 values, then outputting a singular value.

Note: y having (1000,) looks weird, but it's cuz y values are scalar (single values), therefore it doesn't have dimension. So think of it as the same as 1d, 2d, and 3d arrays. But minus 1 to the number of dimensions to get what we have.

Steps in modelling

Now we know what data we have, as well as input and output shapews. Let's see how we can build a neural network model to it.

In TensorFlow, there are typically 3 fundamental steps to creating and training a model.

  1. Creating a model - piece together layer of a neural network yourself (using functional or sequential API) or import previously built models (transfer learning).
  2. Compiling a model - defining how a model's performance should be measured (loss/metrics), and defining how it should improve (optimizer).
  3. Fitting a model - letting the model try to find patterns in the data.

Let's see this in action with Sequential API to build a model for our regression data. We'll step through each one by one.

In[14]:
# Set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# 1. Create the model using the Sequential API
model_1 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1)
])

# 2. Compile the model
model_1.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(), # binary since we are working with 2 classes (0 & 1)
                optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.SGD(),
                metrics=['accuracy'])

# 3. Fit the model
model_1.fit(X, y, epochs=5)

No improvement at all. Let's firstly remind ourselves what more ways we can use to improve our model's accuracy.

Improving a model

To improve our model, we can alter almost every part of the 3 steps we went through before.

  1. Creating a model - piece together layer of a neural network yourself (using functional or sequential API) or import previously built models (transfer learning).
  2. Compiling a model - defining how a model's performance should be measured (loss/metrics), and defining how it should improve (optimizer).
  3. Fitting a model - letting the model try to find patterns in the data.

Remember this image from the previous workbook? These would help us when we're in a pickle... mostly.

For our rehearsing, let's try adding more neurons, another layer, and use the Adam optimizer.

Let's visualize and see what is happening.

Note: Whenever your model performs strangely, or you don't know what's happening with your data, always remember to visualize. Inspect the data, the model, and it's predictions.

To visualize our model's predictions we're going to create a function plot_decision_boundary() which:

  • Takes in a trained model, features (X) and labels (y).
  • Creates a meshgrid of the different X values.
  • Makes predictions across the meshgrid.
  • Plots the predictions as well as a line between the different zones (where each unique class falls).

If this sounds confusing, let's see it in code and it's output.

Note: If you're ever unsure what a function does, try unravel it by writing the code line by line and see what it does. Break into small chunks and see what each part does.

In[18]:
import numpy as np

def plot_decision_boundary(model, X, y):
    """
    Plots the decision boundary created by a model predicting on X.
    This function has been adapted from two phenomenal resources:
    1. CS231n - https://cs231n.github.io/neural-networks-case-study/
    2. Made with ML basics - https://github.com/GokuMohandas/MadeWithML/blob/main/notebooks/08_Neural_Networks.ipynb
    """
    # Define the axis boundaries of the plot and create a meshgrid
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 0.1, X[:, 0].max() + 0.1 # defines the boundaries of the min and max. They have a buffer of 0.1 from the min, and the max of each axis
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 0.1, X[:, 1].max() + 0.1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(x_min, x_max, 100), # linspace(start, stop, num) generates sequence of values that are evenly spaced from start to stop.
                         np.linspace(y_min, y_max, 100)) # create 100 evenly spaced points for xmin, xmax, ymin, and ymax.
    
    # Create X values (we're going to predict on all of these)
    x_in = np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()] # stack 2D arrays together
    # .ravel > NumPy method that flattens a 2D array into 1D. The stack and flattening, allows the pair of coordinates (x and y) be used more efficiently by ML models.

    # Make predictions using the trained model
    y_pred = model.predict(x_in)

    # Check for multi-class
    if model.output_shape[-1] > 1: # checks the final dimension of the model's output chape, shape bigger than 1 = multi classification
        print('doing multiclass classification...')
        # We have to reshape our predictions to get then ready for plotting
        y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1).reshape(xx.shape)
    else:
        print('doing binary classification...')
        y_pred = np.round(np.max(y_pred, axis=1)).reshape(xx.shape)

    # Plot decision boundary
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, y_pred, cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu, alpha=0.7) # filled contour plot, to show x and y positions on the graph, along with the prediction. set alpha/transparency to 0.7 so we can see underneath overlapped dots
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, s=40, cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu) # scatter plot of actual data, with x and y labels.
    plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max()) # last two, sets the max and min limits of the range in meshgrid/data
    plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())

Now we've got a function to plot our model's decision boundary (the cut off point between red and blue dots), let's try it out.

The missing piece: Non-linearity

So we can see the neural network able to model straight lines with abit of guessing/variability. But what about non-straight lines?

To model our classification data, we're going to need some non-linear lines.

The main change we'll add to the model is use the activation keyword.

In[24]:

Finding the best learning rate

Out of all hyperparameters, the most important is the learning rate of the neural network models.

In model_8, we lowered Adam optimizer's learning rate from its default 0.001 to 0.01. Why did we do this? Well, lucky guess you could say.

Just decide to change something in it, and see what results come of it. With practice, you'll start to see what kind of parameters work or don't.

It's very experimental. You build the model, evaluate it, build it, and continue to evaluate it. But there is a trick to help you find the optimal learning rate (at least during the beginning of training).

To do so, we're going to use the following:

  • learning rate callback: Think of callback as extra piece of functionality you can add to your model while its training.
  • Another model (could use the same above)
  • A modified loss curves plot

Note: Default hyperparameters for most neural networks in TensorFlow, are setup to be able to work right out of the box. Where the parameters are tuned to be the best for the entire aggregate of possible problems. It's always a good idea to try the defaults first before adjusting.

In[47]:
tf.random.set_seed(42)

model_9 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

model_9.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', # can use strings here too
                optimizer='Adam', # same to tf.keras.optimizers.Adam() with default settings
                metrics=['accuracy'])

lr_scheduler = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lambda epoch: 1e-4 * 10**(epoch/20)) # traverse a set of learning rate values starting from 1e-4, increasing by 10**(epoch/20) every epoch
                                                                                             # aka increasing learning rate on adam bit by bit per every epoch

# fit model and place lr_scheduler with callbacks
history = model_9.fit(X_train,
                      y_train,
                      epochs=100,
                      callbacks=[lr_scheduler])

Our model has finished training, and let's have a look at training history.

In[48]:
# Checkout the history
pd.DataFrame(history.history).plot(figsize=(10,7), xlabel='epochs');

As the epoch increases, the learning rate exponentially increases.

You can see the model's accuracy going up and then down at specific point depending on the learning_rate.

We can figure this out and it's infliction point, by plotting the loss versus, log-scaled learning rate.

In[49]:
# plot the learning rate versus the loss
lrs = 1e-4 * (10 ** (np.arange(100)/20)) # recreate learning rate rule for x-axis
plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
plt.semilogx(lrs,history.history['loss']) # we want the x-axis (learning rate) to be log scale as to be plotted without heavy skewing (keeping it linear)
plt.xlabel('Learning Rate')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.title('Learning rate vs. loss');

A good rule of thumb when picking the learning rate, is where the loss is decreasing but hasn't fully flattened out. That ends up to be around 0.03 to 0.04 for us.

Now we've got our answer to ideal learning rate, let's implement it in model.

More classification evaluation methods

Along with the visuals we make, there are a number of different evaluation metrics to use on our classification models.

| Metric name/Evaluation method | Definition | Code | ----- | ------ | ----- | | Accuracy | Out of 100% of predictions, how many % of them were correct? | sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score() or tf.keras.metrics.Accuracy() | | Precision | Proportion of true positives over total number of samples. High precision, means less false pos | sklearn.metrics.precision_score() or tf.keras.metrics.Precision() | | Recall | Proportion of true positives over total number of all positive predictions. High recall, means less false negs | sklearn.metrics.recall_score() or tf.keras.metrics.Recall() | | F1-score | Combines precision and recall into one metric (both score weight split equal as default) | sklearn.metrics.f1_score() | | Confusion matrix | Compares predicted values to true values in a grid fashion. If 100% correct, all values will align diagonally | Custom function or sklearn.metrics.plot_confusion_matric() | | Classification report | Collection of main metrics like precision, recall and f1-score | sklearn.metrics.classification_report() |

Note: Every classification problem will require diferent evaluation methods. At least be familiar with the main ones above! ^

Looks like our predictions are in prediction probabilities, rather than the test format of binary.

You'll see this often with outputs of neural networks. Often won't be exact values, but more a probability of how likey they are to be one thing or another.

So a common step you'll see, is converting the predictions into binary labels. We can do this by converting prediction probabilities to their binary form with tf.round().

We can see the highest values are diagonally displayed from top left, to bottom right. Which is a good sign for accuracy of model. But it's a bit difficult to tell from its simplicity.

How about we make a function to make our confusion matrix more visual and nice to look at?

In[59]:
# Note: The following confusion matrix code is a remix of Scikit-Learn's 'plot_confusion_matrix', and made with ML's introductory notebook https://github.com/GokuMohandas/MadeWithML/blob/main/notebooks/08_Neural_Networks.ipynb
import itertools

figsize = (10,10)

# create the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, tf.round(y_preds))
cm_norm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis] # normalizing, 'float' > we'll be dividing, 'cm.sum' to count all values of truth labels and dividing it everytime with each prediction, false or negative
                                                             # aka, this is a percentage calculator, calculating how many percent of the prediction was in 1, in 0, or at another 3rd label.
n_classes = cm.shape[0] # extract true values from column 0

# Let's prettify it
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
# create a matrix plot
cax = ax.matshow(cm, cmap=plt.cm.Blues) # https://matplotlib.org/3.2.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.matshow.html
                                        # matshow > heatmap for our confusion matrix, cmap > to colour our graph with blue to visually represent values on heatmap
                                        # saving it as variable for later modification
fig.colorbar(cax) # add colourbar to reference against the values

# create classes to identify between true values and prediction
classes = False

if classes:
    labels = classes
else:
    labels = np.arange(cm.shape[0])

# label the axes
ax.set(title='Confusion Matrix',
       xlabel='Predicted label',
       ylabel='True label',
       xticks=np.arange(n_classes), # specifying placement of ticks. Ticks are like placeholder of major points/value to the graph, aka the labels that goes on the graph.
       yticks=np.arange(n_classes),
       xticklabels=labels,
       yticklabels=labels)

# Set x-axis labels to bottom
ax.xaxis.set_label_position('bottom')
ax.xaxis.tick_bottom()

# Adjust label size
ax.xaxis.label.set_size(20)
ax.yaxis.label.set_size(20)
ax.title.set_size(20)

# set threshold for diferent colours
threshold = (cm.max() + cm.min()) / 2. # find the midpoint value between min and max. Helps with colouring text annotations, when choosing black, or white, based on the supposed contrast of the colour at the back.

# plot the text on each cell, looping until all text is added
for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])): # i and j, representing true and predicted values respectively
    plt.text(j, i, f'{cm[i, j]} ({cm_norm[i, j]*100:.1f}%)', # format them into percentage of output. Aka out of all 1s that are true, how many are predicted as 1, or 0 as a percentage?
             horizontalalignment='center', # centers text inside the cell
             color='white' if cm[i, j] > threshold else 'black', # text colour based on the contrast of the cell at the back. Done by seeing whether its at the upper half or lower half of values.
             size=15)

Much better! It seems our model has mode almost perfect predictions, but mislabeled a 0 as a 1. (Top right corner)

Working with a larger example (multiclass classification)

We've seen a binary classificaion example (our prediction of the blue and red circle), but what if you had multiple different classes of things?

Say, you were a fashion company and wanted to build a neural network to predict whether a piece of clothing is a shoe, a shirt, or a jacket (3 different options).

When you have more than two classes as an option, this is known as multiclass classification.

Good news is, the things we've learnt so far can be applied to multiclass classification problems as well.

Let's see it in action.

To start, we need data. And we have one as Fashion MNIST built-in. Meaning we can get started straight away.

We can import it using tf.keras.datasets module.

Resource: The following multiclass classification problem has been afapted from the TensorFlow classification guide. A good exercise would be to replicate the TensorFlow guide after following through the examples here.

In[61]:

Let's build a model to figure out the relationship between te pixel values and their labels.

We'll need to make a few changes to our architecture, from binary classification to multiclass classification:

  • The input shape will have to deal with 28x28 tensors (height and width of images).
    • We'll be squishing the input into a tensor (vector) shape (784).
  • The output shape will have to be 10 because we need our model to predict for 10 different classes.
    • We'll change the activation parameter of our output layer be softmax, instead of sigmoid. The sigmoid activation function outputs a series of values between 0 & 1 (same as output shape, which adds up to ~1, aka probability) The index with the highest value is predicted by the model to be the most likely class.
  • We'll need to change our loss function from a binary loss function to a multiclass loss function.
    • More specifically, since our labels are in integer form, we'll use tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(), if our labels were one-hot encoded (e.g. they lookd something like [0,0,1,0,...]), we'd use tf.keras.losses.CategoricalCrossentropy().
  • We'll also use the validation_data parameter when calling the fit() function. This gives us an idea on the performance of the model on the test during training.
In[70]:
# set random seed
tf.random.set_seed(42)

# create the model
model_11 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)), # input layer (have to reshape 28x28 to 784, flatten layer does this for us)
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax') # output shape is 10, activation is softmax
])

# compile the model
model_11.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(), # different loss function for multiclass classification
                 optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),
                 metrics=['accuracy'])

# fit the model
non_norm_history = model_11.fit(train_data,
                                train_labels,
                                epochs=10,
                                validation_data=(test_data, test_labels)) # see how the model performs on the test set during training

In[89]:
# creating a confusion matrix code
import itertools
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# our function needs a different name to sklearn's plot_confusion_matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, classes=None, figsize=(10,10), text_size=15):
    """Makes a labelled confusion matrix comparing predictions and ground truth labels.
    
    If classes is passed, confusion matrix will be labelled, if not, interger class values will be used.
    
    Args:
        y_true: Array of truth labels (must be same shape as y_pred)
        y_pred: Array of predicted labels (must be same shape as y_true)
        classes: Array of class labels (e.g. string form). If 'None', integer labels are used
        figsize: Size of output figure (default=(10,10))
        text_size: Size of output figure test (default=15)
        
    Returns:
        A labelled confusion matrix plot comparing y_true and y_pred

    Example usage:
        make_confusion_matrix(y_true=test_labes, # ground truth test labels
                              y_pred=y_preds, # predicted labels
                              classes=class_names, # array of class label names
                              figsize=(15,15),
                              text_size=10)
    """
    # create the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred) # confusion_matrix() computes the true and predicted value, into a matrix/2d grid
    cm_norm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis] # normalize it, to get the percentage of data residing in a matrix grid, based on total number of true predictions for category '1'. Put this in new axis too
    n_classes = cm.shape[0] # find the number of classes we're dealing with

    # plot the figure and make it pretty
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    cax = ax.matshow(cm, cmap=plt.cm.Blues) # colors will represent how 'correct' it is. Deeper the colour, the more data is in, in one of the boxes
    fig.colorbar(cax) # add colour bar for better comparison to matrix 

    # are there a list of classes?
    if classes:
        labels=classes
    else:
        labels=np.arange(cm.shape[0]) # if no labels, create them numerically based on how many is in the dataset
    
    # label the axes
    ax.set(title='Confusion Matrix',
           xlabel='Predicted label',
           ylabel='True label',
           xticks=np.arange(n_classes), # create enough axis slots for each class
           yticks=np.arange(n_classes),
           xticklabels=labels, # axes will labeled with class names (if they exist) or ints
           yticklabels=labels)
    
    # Make x-axis labels appear on bottom
    ax.xaxis.set_label_position('bottom')
    ax.xaxis.tick_bottom()

    # set the threshold for different colors
    threshold = (cm.max() + cm.min()) / 2. # threshold for colouring of text, which is midpoint between min and max

    # plot the text on each cell
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])): # goes through entire row and column indices for matrix
        plt.text(j, i, f"{cm[i, j]} ({cm_norm[i, j]*100:.1f}%)", # cm[i, j] > the full count of how many times 'i' was predicted as 'j'
                                                                 # cm_norm[i, j] * 100 > normalized values, for percentage of class 'j' being in 'i'
        horizontalalignment='center',
        color='white' if cm[i, j] > threshold else 'black', # white text is used based on threshold that was coded before, else black
        size=text_size)

In[91]:
import random

# Create a function for plotting a random image along with its prediction
def plot_random_image(model, images, true_labels, classes):
    """
    Picks a random image, plots it and labels it with a predicted and truth label.

    Args:
        model: a trained model (trained on data similar to what's in images).
        images: a set of random images (in tensor form).
        true_labels: array of ground truth labels for images.
        classes: array of class names for images.

    Returns:
        A plot of a random image from 'images' with a predicted class label from 'model' as well as the truth class label from 'true_labels'.
    """
    
    # Setup random integer
    i = random.randint(0, len(images))

    # Create predictions and targets
    target_image = images[i]
    pred_probs = model.predict(target_image.reshape(1,28,28)) # reshape 28 by 28 to right shape for model
    pred_label = classes[pred_probs.argmax()]
    true_label = classes[true_labels[i]]

    # Plot the target image
    plt.imshow(target_image, cmap=plt.cm.binary)

    # Change the color of the titles depending on if the prediction is right or wrong
    if pred_label == true_label:
        color='green'
    else:
        color='red'

    # Add xlabel information (prediction/true label)
    plt.xlabel("Pred: {} {:2.0f}% (True: {})".format(pred_label, 100*tf.reduce_max(pred_probs), true_label), 
               color=color) # set colour from our if else table

The weights of the matrix, is the same shape as the input data (28x28, which is 784). And there's a copy of the weights matrix for each neuron in the selected layer (our selected layer has 4 neurons).

Each value in the weights matrix corresponds to how a particular value in the input data influences the network's decisions.

These values are all randomly generated (set by the kernel_initializer parameter when creating a layer, the default is glorot_uniform) which are then updated for better representation of the data by the neural network during training.

Example workflow of how a supervised neural network starts, with using random weight initially, and updating to better represent the data through looking at examples of ideal outputs.

The bias values get initialized as zeroes by default (using the bias_initializer parameter).

The bias vector dictates how much the patterns within the coresponding weights matrix should influence the next layer.

How a model learns (in brief)

We've done a bunch of models, but what really happens under the hood? How does the model exactly learn?

A model learns by updating and improving its weight matrice and bias values of every epoch (in our case, when we call the fit() function).

It does so by comparing the patterns its learned between the data and labels to the actual labels.

If the current patterns (weight matrices and bias values) don't result in a desirable decrease in the loss function (higher loss means worse predictions), the optimizer tries to steer the model to update its patterns in the right way, by trying to decrease loss, and using the true labels as reference.

The process of using real labels as reference for improving model predictions is called backpropagation.

In other words, data and labels pass through a model (forward pass) and it attempts to learn the relationship between the data and labels.

If the learned relationship isn't close to actual relationship, or that it could be inproved, the model goes back through itself (backward pass) and tweaking its weight matrices and bias values to better represent the data.

If all this is confusing, there's some extra cirricular content at the bottom of the workbook.
